1259A - Happy Birthday, Polycarp!
It seems that one of the easiest ways to solve this problem is to iterate over all beautiful numbers up to $$$10^9$$$ and check each of the numbers to ensure that it does not exceed $$$n$$$. First of all, you can iterate over a length from $$$1$$$ to $$$8$$$, supporting a number of the form
11...1
of this length, and inside iterate over a factor for this number from $$$1$$$ to $$$9$$$. The main part of a solution might look like this:
cin >> n;
int b = 0, ans = 0;
for (int len = 1; len <= 9; len++) {
b = b * 10 + 1;
for (int m = 1; m <= 9; m++)
if (b * m <= n)
ans++;
}
cout << ans << endl;
